Patch Set 3:

> (2 comments)
 > 
 > Why isn't this included in your other patch? They're all working
 > towards the same goal and have near identical commit subjects.
 > Either disambiguate them better, or squash them.

Please advise on how to "disambiguate" better. While the commit titles are similar, they nevertheless mention the specific tests being fixed. And the commit messages go into more detail about that. These patches should in no way be squashed, to prevent review changes requested for one test from bogging down the rest of them. Also, here's: a similar set of separate patches consolidated under the same goal which merged in Ocata and which you approved without such objections: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:merged+project:openstack/glance+branch:master+topic:python3-functional-tests

Patch Set 3:

Alexander Bashmakov wrote:

> Please advise on how to "disambiguate" better. While the commit
> titles are similar, they nevertheless mention the specific tests
> being fixed. And the commit messages go into more detail about that.

So when I'm looking for the introduction of a particular issue, I look at titles alone. When I'm skimming them, having a bunch that are nearly identical is confusing, distracting, and a waste of time for the person reviewing history.

> These patches should in no way be squashed, to prevent review
> changes requested for one test from bogging down the rest of them.

I think that reasoning is incredibly faulty. As it stands, the status of these patches proves my point. None of them have merged in spite of their being separate.

> Also, here's: a similar set of separate patches consolidated under
> the same goal which merged in Ocata and which you approved without
> such objections: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:merged+proj
> ect:openstack/glance+branch:master+topic:python3-functional-tests

Two things here:

1. People change, as does their behaviour. Saying I should act as irrationally as I did back then is not even remotely appropriate or mature.

2. You took an impersonal, constructively critical review and made it person. This is highly unprofessional.

3. There's also the element of knowing that the contributor in question dumps reviews and rarely responds to feedback. You on the other hand, have always been receptive to constructive criticism.

Patch Set 3:

My comments inline below.

 > So when I'm looking for the introduction of a particular issue, I
 > look at titles alone. When I'm skimming them, having a bunch that
 > are nearly identical is confusing, distracting, and a waste of time
 > for the person reviewing history.
Ok, that is a fair point. I should have, and plan to make the titles more clear and different from each other. My original purpose was to make them easier to pick out if one is wanting to review all patches related to the py35 goal. But given that they are all consolidated under the same topic, there is really no need to keep the titles very similar.

 > I think that reasoning is incredibly faulty. As it stands, the
 > status of these patches proves my point. None of them have merged
 > in spite of their being separate.
That is not an argument in favor of squashing them. The fact the the other patches have not merged has to do with a dearth of reviewers on Glance and other priorities taking precedence. It has nothing to do with the fact that these are separate commits.

 > Two things here:
 > 
 > 1. People change, as does their behaviour. Saying I should act as
 > irrationally as I did back then is not even remotely appropriate or
 > mature.
 > 
 > 2. You took an impersonal, constructively critical review and made
 > it person. This is highly unprofessional.
 > 
 > 3. There's also the element of knowing that the contributor in
 > question dumps reviews and rarely responds to feedback. You on the
 > other hand, have always been receptive to constructive criticism.

You said two things, but listed 3 :)
I wholeheartedly agree with #3 and appreciate the addendum. Let me address points 1 and 2 together, with which I disagree. This is not a case of making things personal. One of the ways I learned and continue to learn to contribute to OS is by looking at past contribution history. I noticed a precedent that you happened to set previously which is in direct contradiction of your current opinion. If your opinion has changed since then, it is perfectly reasonable for me to ask you to justify that, since negative feedback was given with no justification. That is not personal, if someone else had set that precedent, I would have called them out.
